Here I present my findings that the solar system mirrors atomic systems and has a quantum
mechanical solution to the Schrödinger wave equation based on a base unit of 1 second. I further
suggest that this solution for our spectral class G2V star the Sun, may indicate that life is a
uniform cosmic unfolding throughout the Universe. In this age where we are able to now infer
planets around other stars, including Earth-like planets in the habitable zones, and can obtain
some of the orbital data, that this theory can soon be tested, because major efforts are underway
to build better telescopes and equipment for such inferences, and the the James Webb space
telescope has already been employed and is being geared up for such jobs.

A very interesting thing here is looking at the values generated by the program, the smallest
integer value 1 second produces 6 protons (carbon) and the largest integer value 6 seconds
produces one proton (hydrogen). Beyond six seconds you have fractional protons, and the rest
of the elements heavier than carbon are formed by fractional seconds. These are the
hydrocarbons the backbones of biological chemistry. And carbon is the core element of life.
Here is the code for the program:
#include <stdio.h>
#include <math.h>
int main(int argc, const char * argv[]) {
int n;
float value=0, increment,t=0, p=1.67262E-27, h=6.62607E-34,G=6.67408E-11,
c=299792459,protons[100],r=0.833E-15;
do
{
printf("By what value would you like to increment?: ");
scanf("%f", &increment);
printf("How many values would you like to calculate for t in equation 1 (no more than 100?): ");
scanf("%i", &n);
}
while (n>=101);
{
for (int i=0; i<n;i++)
{
protons[i]=((137*137)/(t*p))*sqrt(h*4*(3.14159)*(r*r)/(G*c));
int intpart=(int)protons[i];
float decpart=protons[i]-intpart;
t=t+increment;
if (decpart<0.25)
{ printf("%.4f protons %f seconds %f decpart \n", protons[i], t-increment, decpart);
}}}}

Discussion
There is strong suggestion in the findings of this theory that life is a uniform cosmic process
throughout the universe. But what is meant by uniform? Well if my Planck constant for the solar
system applies to stars beyond our star system, then many G2 V main sequence stars like our
Sun (yellow-white color and temperature, hydrogen burning) may have habitable planets like
the Earth. The Planck constant for the solar system might be universal because it is here
connected to the proton in a very dynamic way. Uniform might mean five-fold symmetry that is
typical of life on Earth, for example five fingers on each hand, or two arms, two legs and a head,
or two eyes a nose, and a mouth on the face. And it may mean a genetic code like we have, DNA
and RNA, based on purines like adenine, guanine, cytosine, thymine, and uracil, with phosphate
backbones, and ribose sugar. Uniform might imply things like this, but our equations are not
biochemistry but planetary, which might be the conditions for such biology. Uniform here
means subtle variations on an idea, like here on Earth — variations in skin color, or tall/short,
variations in hair color, or four legs with fur, but variations in patterns like stripes or dots.
The idea of uniformity throughout the Universe in life may have begun with the British
astronomer Fred Hoyle. He suggested planets were seeded by one process with the components
for life to take hold and evolve. To do this he figured we needed carbon as universal to have life
as we have it here, based on carbon. Carbon seems to do the job because it has 4 valence
electrons allowing for the long chains of hydrocarbons involving, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus,
and sulfur predominantly. Silicon has four valence electrons as well but readily combines with
oxygen so easily to make SiO2 (silicon dioxide) the primary component of sand and glass, so it is
not available to combine with anything else. Hoyle then had to show how stars make carbon
from lighter elements, which he did in his triple alpha process.
So this is what is called astrobiology or exobiology, that considers not just how life is on Earth,
but how it might be throughout the Universe. There are now textbooks in this fairly new field,
and it is starting to be offered in astronomy departments at universities. With good reason
because though we cannot yet travel the immense distances to the stars, we have begun to be
able to explore the planets of our solar system. We are at that point, with computers and robots
becoming so sophisticated now, that we are able to do this.
I think the Earth/Moon/Sun system might be mathematically part of the development of life.
You can speak of the structure of the solar system even though it changes with time by very
small amounts over millions of years. This is important to understand when I refer to sizes of
the Moon and the planets, and their orbital distances. The whole object of developing a theory
for the way planetary systems form is that they meet the following criterion: They predict the
Titius-Bode rule for the distribution of the planets; the distribution gives the planetary orbital
periods from Newton’s Universal Law of Gravitation. The distribution of the planets is chiefly
predicted by three factors: The inward forces of gravity from the parent star, the outward
pressure gradient from the stellar production of radiation, and the outward inertial forces as a
cloud collapses into a flat disc around the central star. These forces separate the flat disc into
rings, agglomerations of material, each ring from which a different planet forms at its central
distance from the star (it has a thickness). In a theory of planetary formation from a primordial
disc, it should predict the Titius-Bode rule for the distribution of planets.

However the Moon had to be closer to the Earth at this time and its kinetic energy would have
been different in our equation using the kinetic energy of the Moon to get 1 second. However,
Nature magazine covered this in the late 1970’s in an article “Nautiloid growth rhythms and
dynamical evolution the Earth-Moon system” by Peter G.K. Kahn and Stephen M. Pompea
Nature 275 606-611. Fossils of the living fossil the chambered Nautilus were studied. The
Nautilus grows a growth ring that is timed by the Sun, one per day, and a new chamber timed by
the Moon, one per lunar month. These Cephalopods in the Cambrian had 18 growth rings per
chamber and today they have 28. Today the lunar month is 28 days. So it is implied then the
lunar month was 18 days. Thus the Moon’s orbital period was 18 days. From this we can get the
Moon’s distance from the Earth during the Cambrian explosion of life with Kepler’s Law of
planetary motion.
